Encoding + armor
Add:
Framing (start/end markers)
Error-correcting codes (so you can fix flipped bits)
Checksums (so you can reject garbage)
Modulation
Those bits are turned into wiggles in an electromagnetic wave:
flip the phase, tweak the frequency, etc.
Still just: “this phase = 0, that phase = 1”.
Deep Space Network (DSN) dishes
Three huge ground complexes spaced around Earth so at least one can “see” any given probe:
Goldstone (US)
Madrid (Spain)
Canberra (Australia)
Giant antennas (34–70 m) slam a tight radio beam toward the spacecraft on S/X/Ka bands.
Spacecraft side
Has a high-gain antenna (the space dish).
Receives the faint signal, amplifies, demodulates, checks error codes:
if checksum good → accept command
if bad → discard.
Downlink (telemetry)
Reverse path: spacecraft sends science + status back down as super-weak radio.
DSN does insane signal processing to pull a whisper out of cosmic noise.
1.2 Numbers that matter (for you as metaphor)
Distance: Voyager 1 is so far that 1 round-trip ping is 40+ hours.
Speed: radio = speed of light. No “real-time control” beyond Earth orbit; it’s all send instruction, wait, check result.
Power: probe might only transmit a few watts, but focused through the high-gain antenna.
Data rates: deep space = bits per second to kbps, not megabits.
For your architecture, DSN is basically:
Lethani-clean, low-bandwidth, ultra-reliable control channel that never carries hostile code, only intent.
Lots of error-checking, redundancy, and patience to offset distance and weakness.
